summary: The Dallas Cowboys have signed former Minnesota Vikings running back Dalvin Cook to their practice squad, according to multiple reports. Cook, a four-time Pro Bowl selection, visited the Cowboys on Thursday and agreed to a one-year contract. The move comes as Dallas looks to bolster its running back depth behind Ezekiel Elliott. Cook, 27, has rushed for over 1,000 yards in each of the past three seasons and has scored 45 touchdowns in his career. He is expected to provide the Cowboys with another experienced option in the backfield and could potentially see some playing time this season.

summary:
**Summary of News Article Titles:**

This drop was triggered by the company's delay in filing its 10-K financial report, which has raised concerns among investors. Additionally, short seller Hindenburg Research has released a report accusing SMCI of being a "serial recidivist," contributing to the stock's downward trend. Amidst these challenges, some analysts believe that SMCI's stock may be an attractive buying opportunity due to its undervalued status. However, observers are advised to monitor the situation and key price levels as the company addresses these concerns.

name: Nick Chubb
summary: Browns running back Nick Chubb is expected to miss the first four games of the 2024 season as he recovers from a knee injury. Chubb will be placed on the Physically Unable to Perform (PUP) list, which means he cannot practice or play in games for the first six weeks of the regular season. The Browns have not released an official timeline for Chubb's return, but sources indicate that he could be out for longer than the initial four-game suspension. Chubb suffered the injury in Week 1 of the 2023 season and has not played since.

summary: Robert Telles, a former Nevada politician, has been found guilty of murdering investigative journalist Jeff German. Telles was sentenced to life in prison. The case gained national attention as it involved the killing of a reporter who was investigating Telles's conduct as a public official. The trial included witness testimony and closing arguments, and the jury deliberated for several days before reaching a verdict. This high-profile case highlights the importance of protecting journalists and freedom of the press.

name: Delta airlines tire explosion Atlanta
summary: Tragedy struck at a Delta Air Lines facility in Atlanta when a tire explosion claimed the lives of two workers and injured a third. Two individuals, identified as employees of the company, were fatally injured in the incident. The injured worker was reported to be in serious condition. The explosion occurred at Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport, where the Delta employees were reportedly conducting maintenance on an aircraft. The cause of the explosion remains under investigation, and the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers (IAM) Union issued a statement expressing condolences and demanding a thorough investigation. The victims' families and colleagues are mourning the loss of their loved ones.

name: Trump Arlington
summary: Several articles discuss an incident involving Trump campaign staff and an official at Arlington National Cemetery. Some report a physical altercation, while others refer to it as a "verbal confrontation." The visit has sparked controversy, with some critics questioning why former President Trump was allowed to use the cemetery for a political event. The Trump campaign has posted videos of the visit, despite reports of the altercation. Meanwhile, Representative Gerry Connolly has called for the release of any official report regarding the incident. Further reporting indicates that the cemetery's official has described the incident as "rude and disrespectful." The visit has also drawn criticism for its timing, as it occurred on the anniversary of a deadly bombing in Afghanistan. Additionally, Trump has been condemned for rebuking Vice President Harris and President Biden during a speech at the event.

name: Listeria
summary: A deadly Listeria outbreak linked to Boar's Head products has claimed the lives of nine individuals. The outbreak has been traced to a Boar's Head plant where inspections revealed the presence of insects, mold, and mildew. Since early August, the outbreak has resulted in numerous hospitalizations, including three in Massachusetts, and the recent confirmation of five additional fatalities. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) continues to investigate the outbreak and advises consumers to avoid consuming Boar's Head deli meats until further notice.
